                <h2>ALEXANDER ENTERS GRANDEST SPORTS STAGE</h2>
                <p>NFL MVP SHAWN ALEXANDER LEAVES SEATTLE COCOON, ENTERS AMERICA’S GRANDEST SPORTS STAGE</p>
                <p>
                    DETROIT – There is somebody who can beat NFL MVP Shaun Alexander at his own game. Erik Anderson, the founder of the American Foundation for Chess?
                </p>
                <p>
                    Alexander said the Seattle-area entrepreneur is the last person to beat him at one of his many loves outside of football. “Yep, first or second week of the season. But he got lucky,” Alexander said, feigning disgust.
                </p>
                <p>Alexander is at the top of his day-job profession this week, a potential Seahawks free agent, league rushing champion and NFL record holder with 28 touchdowns this season. And he is about to play in its ultimate game, Sunday’s Super Bowl against Pittsburgh. Yet chess is just one of the many sides to Alexander that the nation never sees.</p>
